  == Quality of Experience Modeling

  Traditional approaches to #abbr("qoe") modeling have relied on subjective user studies and objective mathematical models to quantify end-user satisfaction @itu_g1011_qoe_assessment @chikkerur_objective_video_quality_assessment. Subjective methods, while considered the gold standard for accuracy, are expensive, time-intensive, and fundamentally impractical for deployment in real-world, large-scale network environments @duanmu_qoe_index_streaming_video . Objective metrics such as Peak Signal-to-Noise Ratio (#abbr("psnr")) @huynh_thu_scope_validity_psnr and the Structural Similarity Index (#abbr("ssim")) @wang_ssim_image_quality_assessment offer computational efficiency but have been shown to correlate poorly with actual human perception, particularly under complex network impairment conditions @wolf_psnr_video_sequence.

  On the other hand, with the adoption of end-to-end encryption (e.g., HTTPS, QUIC) for multimedia delivery, Deep Packet Inspection (#abbr("dpi")) and payload-based video quality analysis are no longer viable. Consequently, recent literature has pivoted towards inferring #abbr("qoe") metrics directly from encrypted network traffic patterns. A significant challenge in this space is the absence of a universally accepted #abbr("qoe") measurement standard @bentaleb_survey_bitrate_adaptation; for instance, the ITU-T P.1203 model was validated only for specific content conditions, limiting its applicability to modern high-resolution streams.

  Frameworks such as ViCrypt @wassermann_vicrypt_video_qoe have demonstrated the feasibility of using #abbr("ml") to predict video #abbr("qoe") from network-layer features, establishing a strong baseline for passive, encrypted traffic monitoring. Further extending this, contemporary studies have utilized #abbr("ml") models to estimate key #abbr("qoe") indicators for encrypted DASH traffic in modern cellular networks @ml_qoe_dash_5g and live video conferencing platforms @estimating_qoe_mdpi. Research by Izima et al. @izima_video_quality_prediction has further explored #abbr("qoe") prediction under time-varying network loads, highlighting the importance of temporal dynamics in feature design. These works collectively establish that statistical network properties such as packet sizes, (#abbr("iat")), and jitter are strong predictors of application-level events like buffer depletion and stalling, forming the theoretical basis for the feature engineering in this thesis.

  == In-Network #abbr("ml")

  While ML-based #abbr("qoe") prediction is well-established, relying on end-host GPUs or external collector servers introduces non-trivial processing latency and limits scalability in high-throughput environments. Recent advancements in programmable data planes, specifically using the P4 language @p4_language_specification, have enabled the displacement of some monitoring and decision-making logic from the control plane to the data plane @marina_paper. This paradigm shift allows classification and telemetry tasks to execute at line rate, directly within the forwarding hardware, eliminating the round-trip cost of offloading decisions to a separate server.

  Executing complex #abbr("ml") models like #abbr("rf")s at line rate, however, requires specialized hardware mapping, as programmable ASICs such as the Intel Tofino do not natively support recursive branching or floating-point arithmetic. The pForest architecture @busse_grawitz_pforest_in_network_inference introduced the foundational concept of translating context-dependent decision trees into Match-Action Tables (#abbrpl("mat")) for in-network inference, demonstrating that tree traversal can be unrolled across sequential pipeline stages. Building upon this paradigm, frameworks like Planter @planter_paper have formalized and automated the mapping of a broad range of ensemble #abbr("ml") models, including #abbr("rf")s, gradient boosted trees, and support vector machines, into programmable switches, significantly lowering the barrier for in-network #abbr("ml") deployment. Other recent works have explored resource-efficient implementations of tree-based models using feature sharing and knowledge distillation @empowering_in_network_classification, reducing #abbr("tcam") pressure by sharing common decision nodes across trees. Hybrid approaches, such as IIsy @iisy_framework, partition the classification task between the data plane and a co-located control-plane agent, relaxing hardware constraints while preserving low-latency inference for the majority of traffic. These methodologies collectively provide the architectural foundation for our approach of translating a unified #abbr("rf") model into unrolled physical pipeline stages using Ternary Content-Addressable Memory (#abbr("tcam")).



