  == Benchmarking and Hardware Constraints

  Evaluating the performance of in-network #abbr("ml") models requires a rigorous understanding of the strict physical constraints imposed by programmable ASICs. Comprehensive surveys on in-network machine learning @in_network_ml_survey have characterized the fundamental bottlenecks of devices such as the Intel Tofino: available #abbr("sram") and #abbr("tcam") capacity, Very Long Instruction Word (VLIW) instruction slot budgets, and a hard limit on the number of physical pipeline stages. These constraints are not merely engineering inconveniences; they define a hard feasibility boundary that determines whether a given model can be compiled and deployed at all.

  Studies evaluating hybrid in-network classification frameworks, such as IIsy @iisy_framework, emphasize the complex, multi-dimensional trade-offs between a model's predictive accuracy and its hardware resource footprint, showing that naive model translation routinely exceeds available pipeline resources. Furthermore, because the Tofino architecture enforces a strict Directed Acyclic Graph (#abbr("dag")) for table execution, the recursive branching inherent in standard decision trees must be aggressively flattened before compilation @in_network_topology_survey. Feature selection therefore plays a dual role: beyond its conventional impact on statistical performance, it directly determines the #abbr("tcam") and #abbr("vliw") instruction budget consumed by each pipeline stage. Recent work by Xie et al. @empowering_in_network_classification has demonstrated that knowledge distillation can compress decision tree ensembles into shallower structures that respect these stage limits without significant accuracy loss. These findings directly motivate the benchmarking methodology adopted in this thesis, in which feature count, tree depth, and ensemble size are systematically swept to map the feasibility boundary on Tofino 2 hardware.
